<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Islamic Group Claims Responsibility </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Islamic Group Claims Responsibility </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3103190094 Paris AFP in English 1744 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3103190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, March 31 (AFP) -- A powerful bomb exploded at 
a bank in the Egyptian capital on Thursday [31 March], damaging 
the building and nearby cars, but causing no casualties, police 
said. 
  Witnesses had earlier said several passers-by were lightly 
injured by the blast, which blew out the building's windows. 
  The outlawed Islamic militant group al-Jama'ah al-Islamiyah 
[Islamic Group] later said it had placed a time bomb under a 
parked car which exploded outside the branch of the Egyptian 
Trade Development Bank. 
  The booby-trapped car and four others parked nearby were 
destroyed when they caught fire. 
  The al-Jama'ah said in a statement sent to AFP that the 
attack had been carried out "in revenge for the torture and 
humiliations inflicted on Islamic detainees." 
  It was the first bomb explosion at a bank during opening 
hours, despite a series of such bombings in recent months. 
  The al-Jama'ah, which has been waging a two-year violent 
campaign against the secular government of President Husni 
Mubarak, previously claimed responsibility for about 10 bombings 
this month. 
  The statement warned that more attacks would follow to 
avenge 
human rights violations in Egypt's prisons, which it alleged had 
"increased in recent days." 
  It also repeated accusations that banks were involved in 
usury by charging interest, which is outlawed by the Koran. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

