<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Committee Delegates Begin Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Committee Delegates Begin Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Release of `Militant' Prisoners Sought </H4>

<F P=102> NC0304143394 Paris AFP in English 1357 3 Apr GMT 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0304143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, April 3 (AFP) -- The PLO wants Islamic 
militant prisoners held by Israel to be included in any accord 
on the release of Palestinian detainees, PLO chief negotiator 
Nabil Sha'th said here Sunday [3 April]. 
  "All Palestinian prisoners are our responsibility, whether 
they belong to (the Islamic Resistance Movement) Hamas or not," 
Sha'th told AFP. 
  "The question of the release of prisoners will be examined 
today (Sunday) or tomorrow, and the Hamas prisoners remain the 
main problem," Sha'th said, adding that the releases would take 
place in stages after an accord to launch Palestinian autonomy 
was signed. 
  Israel and the PLO started intensive negotiations here 
Sunday 
to launch Palestinian self-rule in Gaza and Jericho within 10 
days, after a break of five weeks because of the Hebron massacre. 
  Israel has freed more than 1,000 Palestinian prisoners since 
the autonomy negotiations began last October. 
  Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin announced Sunday that more 
Palestinian prisoners would be freed and others who had been 
deported or fled would be allowed to return to the territories. 
  "These measures will concern only those wanted or expelled, 
who do not have blood on their hands, grassroots militants and 
not frontline political leaders," he said. 
  A Foreign Ministry official said the majority of the 10,000 
Palestinians still in Israeli jails would be released in several 
stages. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

