Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Interviewed on Somalia, Yemeni Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Interviewed on Somalia, Yemeni Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0104194294 Cairo ESC Television in Arabic 1620 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0104194294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo ESC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Muhammad Salim Basindwah by </F>
Safa' Hijazi in Cairo, date not given; from the "Arabs' Home" 
program--recorded] 
  [Text] [Hijazi] Mr. Yemeni Foreign Minister and Chairman of 
the 101st session of the Arab Foreign Ministers' Council: 
Following the withdrawal of the international forces from 
Somalia, which coincided with the signing of the national 
reconciliation accord among the Somali leaders in Nairobi, what 
is the role of the Arab forces? Was this topic placed on the 
agenda? 
  [Basindwah] At this session the council was informed that 
some Arab states that have contributed forces to the 
peacekeeping troops in Somalia intend to withdraw their forces. 
Naturally, if the Somalis agree among themselves and engage in 
a quiet and objective dialogue, they will not need forces to 
safeguard their security and stability. It seems that the 
existing situation in Somalia will not continue. Somalia will 
inevitably emerge from its current crisis, God willing. 
  [Hijazi] Yemen is a member of the Arab League. Yemen's 
security is part of Arab national security. How can Yemen 
overcome its domestic crisis and what are the latest 
developments in this crisis? 
  [Basindwah] Thank you for your question. On this occasion I 
would like to make it clear that the situation in Yemen is now 
better than before. The cabinet convened in Aden on Wednesday. 
It reconvened in Aden on Sunday. The cabinet is expected to 
meet in Ta'izz tomorrow. The Presidential Council will meet in 
Sanaa tomorrow. We hope all constitutional establishments will 
resume their work in Sanaa within one month. Naturally, if what 
has happened in Yemen had happened in another Arab country or 
another developing country, civil war would have broken out. 
Despite the passage of seven months since the crisis began, we 
Yemenis have not been dragged into a civil war or ferocious 
infighting. This proves that despite our differences and 
disputes, we have been able to steady our nerves and apply 
political pressure on each other without reaching the level of a 
civil war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

