<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Says Regime Harboring, Training `Terrorists' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Says Regime Harboring, Training `Terrorists' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0104081194 Cairo AL-WAFD in Arabic 28 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> NC0104081194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-WAFD </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Majdi Hilmi] </F>
  [Text] The Sudanese opposition National Democratic Grouping 
has affirmed that the Sudanese regime's policy is to divide 
Sudan and to foment disturbances among its sects and people. 
  In a memorandum sent to Arab foreign ministers, the grouping 
pointed out that the regime has obstructed the Constitution, 
dissolved parties and democratic unions, and launched ethnic war 
against the south. This, the grouping added, threatens Sudan's 
unity and invites foreign intervention. The grouping accused 
the regime of harboring and training terrorists in Sudan. It 
said that the regime is providing terrorists with weapons, 
funds, and passports. The grouping maintained that it has 
information that terrorists come from various Arab countries to 
training camps in Sudan. 
  In its memorandum, the Sudanese grouping urged the Arab 
League to intercede and stop the ongoing war in southern Sudan. 
The grouping also called for removing the regime and setting up 
a democratic authority that would respect the right of 
citizenship; separate religion from politics; recognize 
religious, cultural, and ethnic diversity; and recognize the 
independence of the judiciary and the legal profession. The 
grouping voiced its support for the unity of Sudan and its 
people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

