<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Says U.S. Should Urge Israel To Sign NPT </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Says U.S. Should Urge Israel To Sign NPT </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304120094 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0955 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0304120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary] </F>
  [Excerpts] A spokesman of the International Atomic Energy 
Agency [IAEA] in an interview described Israel's refusal to sign 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty [NPT] as the main obstacle 
in the way of the Middle Eastern countries' cooperation with 
that international organization. [passage omitted] 
  The refusal of countries such as Israel to join the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty makes countries who have signed the 
treaty feel that their cooperation with the IAEA does not 
provide them with any kind of guarantee against a threat posed 
by the countries who are not members of the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty. That matter has not only created an 
obstacle in the way of cooperation between the Middle Eastern 
countries and the IAEA, it has also created a problem for 
international cooperation in that context. 
  The acknowledgement of the IAEA spokesman of that problem 
reveals the fact that if this situation is not addressed, it is 
not possible to pin much hope on the nuclear nonproliferation 
programs. 
  At a time when America, together with other countries and in 
cooperation with the IAEA, is exerting pressure on countries 
such as North Korea in order to facilitate the inspection of its 
installations suspected of prohibited nuclear activity, the 
signatories of the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty expect that 
pressure is also exerted on countries such as Israel who have 
not signed the treaty and have not accepted any nonproliferation 
commitment, so that they accept nuclear nonproliferation. 
  Undoubtedly, that measure would serve international peace 
and 
stability as it can reduce obstacles in the way of nuclear 
nonproliferation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

