<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Accuses U.S. of `Provocative' Acts in Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Accuses U.S. of `Provocative' Acts in Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304131194 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1000 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0304131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary] </F>
  [Excerpts] Recent news reports from the Korean peninsula 
speak of the continuation of the American interventionist policy 
in that region. 
  During the past few days, Washington has, once again, 
brought 
serious crisis to the Korean peninsula through its provocative 
acts such as the announcement of stationing Patriot missiles in 
South Korea and deciding to resume its joint maneuvers with 
North Korea. [passage omitted] 
  Paying attention to the current situation in the east Asia 
region and the Pacific Ocean makes it clear that the American 
policy aimed at creating tension in the Korean peninsula is 
intended as a long-term measure. 
  The east Asia region is the focus of attention of the big 
powers, such as America, because it seems that that region would 
play a more significant role in international developments in 
the future. Particularly that the Pacific Ocean region has, 
during the past few years, turned into an international focal 
point, and the rate of growth in some of the countries of the 
region, such as China, has reached a level that is currently 
unachievable by advanced industrial countries. It is clear that 
the continuation of such a trend, which is achieved through the 
continuation of efforts to maintain stability in the region, 
would force America to withdraw its 6,000-strong force from the 
Korean peninsula, which would mean losing its economic or 
military control of the region. That is an issue which, 
according to the White House politicians, contradicts the 
American strategy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

