<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Husayni, al-Majali Hold Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Husayni, al-Majali Hold Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0304170194 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1600 GMT 3 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0304170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Faysal al-Husayni, head of the Palestinian 
delegation to the peace negotiations, hailed the great efforts 
and continuous support Jordan has extended and is extending to 
the current restoration works of the Dome of the Rock. 
  He added: What has been achieved there so far is considered 
a very great accomplishment which has rescued the Dome of the 
Rock. We can only express our thanks and gratitude to Jordan for 
what it has done in this field. 
  In a press statement after meeting with Prime Minister Dr. 
'Abd-al-Salam al-Majali at the Prime Ministry today, al-Husayni 
emphasized the importance of the Jordanian role and the support 
the Jordanian Government extends for the efforts of the 
religious establishments in Jerusalem in order to protect the 
holy shrines there. 
  He said it was agreed that the Islamic Awqaf Establishment 
will shoulder full responsibility for restoration actions in the 
holy al-Aqsa Mosque and the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. 
  He said the enormity of the events and the circumstances 
surrounding us require us to boost current coordination to reach 
the level expected from us during the next stage. 
  He added that during his meeting with Dr. al-Majali, which 
was also attended by Dr. Jawad al-'Anani, minister of state for 
cabinet affairs and information minister, and the Palestinian 
ambassador in Amman, he discussed several issues, including 
Jerusalem. Great emphasis was placed on this subject and on 
concentrating on bilateral coordination concerning this 
important subject. 
  Answering a question by the Jordanian news agency on the 
Cairo agreement, which the PLO and Israel recently signed, 
al-Husayni said: Expediting Israeli withdrawal and starting to 
implement the agreement will undoubtedly be a step forward, and 
we hope that Israel will apply the agreement in a manner that 
serves the spirit of the agreement. 
  On the international observers who will be deployed in 
Hebron, and whether their number is enough to protect the 
population of this city, al-Husayni said that what is enough to 
protect the population in Hebron is an Israeli withdrawal and 
the uprooting of the Israeli settlements in the area. He added 
the international presence is something new that will 
undoubtedly serve the Palestinian position, and that although it 
is not enough to protect the Palestinians, it will be an 
assisting factor. 
  The meeting discussed in detail the situation in Jerusalem 
and the need to preserve its Arab character, as well as the 
restoration works on of the Dome of the Rock and the holy 
al-Aqsa Mosque. 
  At the meeting, it was agreed that the subject of Jerusalem 
is one of the most important issues, therefore, the two sides 
emphasized the need to activate the Jerusalem Committee that 
Jordan and the PLO had agreed to set up within the framework of 
comprehensive coordination between Jordan and the PLO. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

