<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rockets Shake Kabul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rockets Shake Kabul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0104172694 Paris AFP in English 1648 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0104172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad, April 1 (AFP) -- Forces opposing Afghan 
President Borhanoddin Rabbani killed and wounded inhabitants 
Friday [1 April] in a hail of rockets, loyalist radio Kabul said. 
  The broadcast, monitored here, said the attack came on the 
eve of a planned visit by a special United Nations peace mission 
led by Mahmoud Mestiri. 
  The UN team is to leave Islamabad for Kabul Saturday for 
talks with Rabbani, his rival, Prime Minister Golboddin 
Hekmatyar, and other factional leaders to explore ways of ending 
13 weeks of fighting for control of Kabul. 
  The radio, controlled by Rabbani loyalists, blamed the 
attack 
on Hekmatyar and his military ally, Abdoul Rashid Dostam, leader 
of the Uzbek militia, and said it came despite their pledge to 
hold a temporary ceasefire from dawn Friday to facilitate the UN 
visit. 
  The radio said people were killed and wounded but it gave no 
figures. 
  No confirmation was immediately available from the rival 
side. 

</TEXT>

