<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Meet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security, Civilian Affairs Committees Meet </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th, Shahaq Comment on Talks </H4>

<F P=102> NC0404142494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1347 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0404142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 4 Apr (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and head of the 
Palestinian side to the Gaza-Jericho Committee meetings, has 
stressed that the main objective of the Security Committee 
meeting today is to complete the negotiations concerning the 
establishment of the Palestinian police force, the timetable for 
the force's entry, and the date the vanguards will arrive in the 
Arab territories. 
  In statements before starting the Palestinian-Israeli 
negotiations today, Dr. Sha'th said the Legal Affairs Committee 
is expected to begin its work today after legal advisers arrive 
from the West Bank and Gaza. Sha'th said several Palestinians 
from the occupied territories are expected to arrive today to 
take part in the meetings of the committee in charge of 
transferring power. The committee started its work in Cairo 
today. 
  In his statements, Dr. Sha'th said the delegates will also 
discuss the possibility of drawing up a timetable for the 
release of the Palestinian prisoners and detainees. He noted 
that the committee stemming from the Gaza-Jericho Committee will 
meet today and will continue working day and night to achieve an 
agreement as soon as possible. He said several Norwegians from 
the international observer force will arrive in Cairo today. 
  General Amnon Shahaq, Israeli deputy chief of staff and head 
of the Israeli side to the negotiations, said this round of 
talks will continue until Wednesday evening. He said he hoped 
that positive results would be achieved as soon as possible. 
  Brigadier General 'Abd-al-Razzaq al-Yahya, head of the 
Palestinian side to the Security Committee, expects that an 
agreement will be reached very soon, noting that if progress is 
achieved in the talks, the negotiations concerning the 
Palestinian police force will be concluded today. 
  Brig. Gen. al-Yahya affirmed that Palestinian President 
'Arafat will arrive in Cairo tomorrow, Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

