<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Group of Deportees To Leave Cairo for Gaza </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    First Group of Deportees To Leave Cairo for Gaza </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0404184794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1800 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0404184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 4 Apr (MENA)--Official Palestinian sources 
have stated that the first group of political deportees, whose 
return Israel has approved, will leave Cairo for the Gaza Strip 
tomorrow, Tuesday. 
  Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin announced earlier that 
Israel has consented to the return of 48 deportees. 
  Their return is part of the confidence-building measures 
between the Palestinian and Israeli peoples after the signing of 
the Declaration of Principles in Washington on 13 December 1993. 
  [In a related, Tunis-datelined report, Paris AFP in English 
at 1734 GMT on 4 April adds the following: "Seventeen 
Palestinian exiles left here Monday bound for their homes in the 
occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank. 
  ["The 17 were part of a group of 46 Palestinians allowed to 
return under an Israeli-PLO security accord signed in Cairo last 
Thursday. They will travel via Jordan and Egypt. 
  ["Six of the Palestinians flew in to Tunis earlier Monday. 
  ["The 11 others had lived in Tunisia since being expelled 
for 
belonging to the mainstream Fatah faction led by Palestine 
Liberation Organisation Chairman Yasir 'Arafat and participating 
in the intifadah, or uprising, in the occupied territories. 
  ["Five will return to the West Bank from Jordan via the 
Allenby bridge and the other 12 will enter Gaza from Egypt."] 

</TEXT>

