<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Peres Seen Changing Stand on Russian Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin, Peres Seen Changing Stand on Russian Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0504100394 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 5 Apr 94 p A3 </F>
<F P=103> TA0504100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] Israel has changed its stand regarding Russia's 
involvement in the peace process. This emerges from remarks 
made by Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres in yesterday's cabinet session. Peres said that 
"we should treat the Russians with respect," reminding the 
ministers that there are 1.5 million Jews in Russia. "We have 
no business expressing reservations about Russia's involvement," 
he said. 
  Rabin said that the United States praised the role the 
Russians played in the activity vis-a-vis the Serbs in the 
Bosnia crisis. "We have special relations with the United 
States, expressed through aid and strategic cooperation, but 
Russian foreign policy is more active than in the past and is 
not negative," Rabin said. 
  The prime minister did not reiterate the claim he made 
during 
the past several weeks that Russia should coordinate its moves 
on the peace process with the United States. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

