<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Prepares Working Paper on Golan Security </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Prepares Working Paper on Golan Security </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0504112694 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 5 Apr 94 p A1 </F>
<F P=103> TA0504112694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Foreign Ministry recently prepared its first 
working paper on security arrangements for the Golan Heights in 
the framework of a peace a agreement with Syria. The document 
does not address the issue of withdrawal from the Golan Heights 
or its extent in the framework of the arrangement; rather, it 
examines the foundations of security arrangements between Israel 
and Syria, such as demilitarizing territories, thinning out 
forces, setting up early warning stations, and deploying 
international supervisors. 
  The document was presented to Foreign Minister Shim'on 
Peres, 
Foreign Ministry top echelons, and senior members of the defense 
establishment. The document is based on analyses of research by 
HA'ARETZ's military commentator Ze'ev Schiff and by Brigadier 
General (Reserves) Arye Shalev and which examined possible 
security arrangements between Israel and Syria. 
  Two days ago, Peres held a discussion with his ministry's 
top 
officials on an arrangement with Syria. Over the past few days, 
sources in the ministry have been saying that after completing 
the agreement with the PLO, "we will race toward Syria." 
  In the discussion, Peres told the ministry staffers to 
prepare proposals for the development of characteristics of 
normalization in the arrangement with Syria, such as economic 
ties between the two countries. Several ideas in this respect 
have already been raised at the Foreign Ministry. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

