<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ghawshah on Negotiations, Police Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ghawshah on Negotiations, Police Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0404120294 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 4 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0404120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with PLO Executive Committee member </F>
Samir Ghawshah, in Tunis, by Fawzi al-Jundi, in Cairo, date not 
given; from the "Dialogue From Afar" program -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Al-Jundi] Dr. Samir Ghawshah, what new principles 
must the upcoming Palestinian-Israeli negotiations be based on 
after a full month of hiatus following the al-Ibrahimi Mosque 
massacre? How do the Palestinians envision the next talks? 
  [Ghawshah] Undoubtedly, the negotiations will be based on 
the 
practical implementation of the Declaration of Principles. But 
we can say that the new talks must focus on accelerating the 
Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho as a practical 
preparation for the full implementation of the Declaration of 
Principles. This will be the first step in the interim stage 
before subsequent steps are taken to reach the final stage. 
  [Al-Jundi] Do you believe that the arrival of the first 
groups of Palestinian police in Gaza beginning on Tuesday is a 
real beginning to the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement? 
  [Ghawshah] The arrival of the first group of police is part 
of the latest agreement on the security measures following the 
Hebron massacre. We are supposed to begin these moves within 
days, on Thursday at the latest, for the entry of the first 
battalion of the Palestinian police force. We believe that this 
is the beginning of a tangible step that must be followed by 
others. We will discuss a timetable for the entry of the 
Palestinian police as soon as possible during the negotiations. 
  [Al-Jundi] Do you think that the Palestinian police force, 
still in its initial stage, can protect the Palestinian people 
under the occupation, or must international forces impose 
themselves at this stage? 
  [Ghawshah] The Palestinian police will face no problem 
except 
from one side, the armed settlers. This is a major 
responsibility that also rests on the shoulders of the Israeli 
police. International observers must be deployed in areas where 
Palestinian forces are not, such as Hebron. But for us, we 
believe the Palestinian police force, when its deployment is 
completed, can perform its duty and face all eventualities, 
including aggression by settlers, especially in Gaza and Jericho. 
  [Al-Jundi] Has the relationship among the Palestinian force, 
the Israeli Army, and the Jewish settlers been decided? 
  [Ghawshah] This is one of the points being discussed at the 
Cairo negotiations. 
  [Al-Jundi] Dr. Samir Ghawshah, the Palestinians have asked 
that the Palestinian-Israeli talks be transferred to Cairo 
instead of Washington. This is because of the Egyptian 
diplomacy's clear activity in reconciling the two sides at the 
negotiating table, which is known as positive mediation. 
  [Ghawshah] There is undoubtedly a big qualitative difference 
in the role and effort. Before anything else, Egypt is an Arab 
country. It has its clear position in supporting the rights of 
the Palestinian people, and it has a positive role in pushing 
the negotiations toward the practical implementation of the UN 
resolutions, including Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338. 
In addition, Egypt knows the details and it is geographically 
close. This makes the Egyptian role effective. On the other 
hand, so far the United States has not been playing its full 
role. It has not been an active partner. U.S. officials have 
often said that they would leave the Palestinian and Israeli 
negotiators without intervention in their negotiations. But the 
fact was that the Americans were biased toward the Israelis. In 
short, we can say that the Egyptian role is outstanding. The 
efforts of Egyptian diplomacy were clear in both the 
negotiations and in supporting the struggle of the Palestinian 
people until they achieve their full rights, including their 
rights to repatriation, self-determination, and the 
establishment of an independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem 
as its capital. 
  [Al-Jundi] Thank you. 
  [Ghawshah] You are welcome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

