<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Washington Meeting on Ship Inspections To Be Held </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Washington Meeting on Ship Inspections To Be Held </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0504075494 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 5 Apr 94 pp 1, 25 </F>
<F P=103> JN0504075494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Caroline Faraj in Amman] </F>
  [Text] An expanded meeting will be held tomorrow Wednesday 
[6 April] comprising representatives of U.S. Government 
departments and bodies concerned with foreign affairs to discuss 
available options concerning the U.S. Navy's inspection of ships 
bound for the Port of al-'Aqabah. 
  Well-informed sources have said that a number of concerned 
U.S. departments and institutions are trying to obstruct the 
holding of this meeting. However, the U.S. State Department 
intends to make a final decision during Wednesday's meeting. 
  A political observer believes that the U.S. State 
Department's inclination toward making a decision should lead to 
a positive one in Jordan's favor. This expected decision will 
be the result of the clear and frank stand expressed by His 
Majesty King Husayn during his meeting with ambassadors of the 
five permanent members of the UN Security Council last week. 
  The previous meeting scheduled for last Thursday was 
postponed for reasons the U.S. State Department spokesman said 
were connected with fixing an appropriate date and time among 
the bodies concerned with foreign affairs. 
  It is worth noting that three months ago Jordan proposed the 
appointment of a third technical and neutral party such as 
Lloyd's Register to inspect ships at the Port of al-'Aqabah 
rather than by the U.S. Navy in the Straits of Tiran as the 
situation is now. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

