<H3> <TI>   Paris Economic Talks Reportedly To Conclude </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paris Economic Talks Reportedly To Conclude </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0504105994 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1000 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0504105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cautious optimism is being voiced on the Israeli 
side on the eve of the resumption of the economic talks with the 
Palestinians in Paris. Close to 70 percent of the issues have 
been finalized, and the sides plan to conclude the remaining 30 
percent in the sessions scheduled to begin tomorrow. Our 
economic affairs correspondent Shlomi Stein reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Stein] There has been a turning point in 
the Israeli position: Attainment of the economic accord is no 
longer a prerequisite for the signing of a comprehensive 
agreement with the Palestinians. Commenting on the need to 
conclude all outstanding issues before signing the agreement, 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin sounded less categorical this 
morning. 
  [Rabin] The least we need is a macro framework -- which must 
also be included in the agreement -- or temporary arrangements, 
which we could implement until a full economic accord is 
attained. 
  [Stein] In previous rounds, Israel presented to the 
Palestinians a 40-page draft accord, 70 percent of which has 
already been worked out and finalized with the Palestinians. 
Finance Minister Avraham Shohat noted today that his ministry 
has drafted a contingency plan in the event that Israel 
evacuates Gaza and Jericho before attaining a full economic 
accord and no longer has full influence over what is done in the 
field. 
  [Shohat] We have worked out an alternative, which we will 
present to the Palestinians. In practical terms, it is a 
one-sided move because it does not stem from an agreement on 
cooperation. 
  [Stein] Shohat voiced cautious optimism today, on the eve of 
his departure for Paris at the head of the Israeli delegation. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

