<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Leads Delegation on Visit to Amman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Leads Delegation on Visit to Amman </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Paper Views Need To Foster Ties </H4>

<F P=102> JN0604083694 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 6 Apr 94 pp 1, 27 </F>
<F P=103> JN0604083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Distinguished Brotherly Relations"] </F>
  [Text] Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat's recurrent 
visits to Jordan and his meetings with his brother His Majesty 
King Husayn reflect the distinguished brotherly relations and 
mutual confidence between the two fraternal peoples. They also 
underscore the importance of continuing coordination, 
consultation, and cooperation between Jordan and the PLO. 
  President 'Arafat's working visit yesterday came in the wake 
of important political developments regarding the various 
aspects of the Palestine question. This situation necessitated 
discussing these developments with the Jordanian leadership as 
is customary in accordance with the firmly-established 
traditions and characteristics marking the fraternal 
Jordanian-Palestinian relations. 
  The two political leaderships and peoples are aware of the 
need to intensify bilateral relations of coordination and 
cooperation out of their awareness of the difficulties facing 
the Palestinian action at this stage. These difficulties 
require entrenching unity of the Arab fold and fostering 
Jordanian-Palestinian relations in order to face the 
developments of this stage. 
  No Arab country is more concerned with or affected by the 
Palestine question than Jordan. Therefore, Jordan has always 
given Palestine--land, cause, and people--constant attention and 
sincere effort out of its eagerness to restore rights and lands 
to their legitimate owners and rescue the shrines, headed by 
holy Jerusalem, from impending dangers. 
  While watching the current developments of the Palestine 
question and while witnessing a turning point in the efforts to 
activate the first article of the Declaration of Principles, we, 
along with the brothers in Palestine, look forward 
optimistically to the day, which we hope is imminent, when the 
occupation ends and our brothers regain their freedom and right 
to self-determination. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

