<H3> <TI>   Rabin Testifies at Shamgar Commission Hearings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin Testifies at Shamgar Commission Hearings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0604103294 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1000 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0604103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A few minutes ago, Yitzhaq Rabin, the prime 
minister and defense minister, wrapped up his testimony before 
the Shamgar commission. His testimony lasted five hours and was 
given on camera. The prime minister came out from a side door 
and refused to answer journalists' questions. Our legal affairs 
correspondent Hadar Vismonsky reports: 
  Yitzhaq Rabin, the prime minister and defense minister whose 
face we did not see today at all because he walked in and came 
out through a side door to evade the cameras, gave a long 
testimony. For five long hours, Rabin was questioned on camera 
by the five members of the commission of inquiry. He was 
accompanied by the legal adviser of the Prime Minister's Office 
and by Cabinet Secretary Elyaqim Rubinstein. 
  The prime minister's testimony actually concluded the 
commission's 15th day of work and the first stage of the 
hearings. Within the next few weeks, the commission members will 
meet in order to formulate their initial conclusions and to 
decide whether any people are liable to be affected by these 
conclusions. If there are such people, they will be sent 
warning letters and be summoned for another hearing, this time 
accompanied by their lawyers. 
  As said, the first stage of the Shamgar commission's work is 
over. Over the next few weeks, the commission will proceed with 
consultations. 

</TEXT>

