<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres Urges Ramon Not To Quit Labor Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0604064694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0600 GMT 6 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0604064694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres says he would prefer 
to advance the negotiations with Jordan at this point, but 
regretfully, that side has recently evinced hesitancy. When 
asked which country was our first priority, Syria or Jordan, 
Minister Peres replied: A great deal depends on them; we will 
be serious with whoever is serious. 
  Interviewed by our correspondent Karmit Gay this morning, 
Minister Peres called on Knesset Member [MK] Hayim Ramon not to 
quit Labor both for his and the party's sake. Shim'on Peres 
revealed that he had met twice with Hayim Ramon last week to try 
to talk him out of his plan. Peres said Ramon belongs in the 
government, and his stepping down had been a blunder. 
  The foreign minister rejected Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi 
Beilin's accusations, saying no one was pushing MK Ramon out of 
the party. 
  Minister 'Uzi Bar'am has also said that Ramon should remain 
in Labor. He criticized Labor Secretary General Zvili's 
remarks, made in Washington this morning, against Hayim Ramon. 

</TEXT>

