<F P=103> TA0604060894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knesset Member [MK] Hayim Ramon is expected to 
announce on 10 April whether he will run on an independent list 
in the Histadrut elections. Our correspondent reports that Mr. 
Ramon invited Likud MK Me'ir Shitrit to fill the second slot on 
his list. MAPAM [United Workers Party] has agreed to join 
Ramon's list, while Meretz is yet to decide its stand. 
  MK Me'ir Shetrit said he was still undecided whether to make 
the move. The Likud candidate for Histadrut chief, MK Ya'aqov 
Shamay, said Hayim Ramon's announcements might be designed to 
pressure Yitzhaq Rabin to reinstate him as cabinet minister. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin said it would be tragedy 
for the Labor Party if Hayim Ramon left it to run independently 
for the position of Histadrut chief. He believed the public 
health issues over which Ramon had waged a struggle are valid, 
but the thinking that these issues could be solved outside the 
party was erroneous. Yosi Beilin leveled criticism at senior 
Labor officials for showing Ramon the way out, as he put it. I 
would do everything possible to prevent his secession from the 
party, the deputy foreign minister told our correspondent this 
morning. 

