Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fadlallah Comments on Pope-Rabin Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fadlallah Comments on Pope-Rabin Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0504171694 Beirut AL-'AHD in Arabic 25 Mar 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> NC0504171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut AL-'AHD </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] His Eminence Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad Husayn 
Fadlallah has stated that the enemy Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin's visit to the Vatican and his audience with the pope "is 
an indulgence for the enemy absolving him of shedding the blood 
of 56 worshippers." 
  In an interview, Fadlallah said that when Rabin visits the 
Vatican and is warmly received, we want to ask: Is the Vatican 
a West European country like the others or a Christian mission? 
Is it operating in its capacity as the Church, guided by its 
Christian values, or as a state operating according to 
international balances? [passage omitted] 
  His eminence continued: The Vatican always spoke of 
internationalizing Jerusalem first and the holy shrines second. 
It also spoke of the freedom of religion and even regarded 
Jerusalem as its very own cause. This time the pope did not 
discuss Jerusalem with Rabin, as Rabin said. The Vatican did 
not deny Rabin's story. 
  Fadlallah asked: If the pope did not discuss Jerusalem with 
Rabin or the need to protect unarmed Palestinians by sending in 
international forces and if Rabin did not ask him to mediate in 
the negotiations, what was the visit about? The affair then 
represents an indulgence for the Jews and a new recognition that 
gives "Israel" new moral strength to add to the strength it 
already has. [passage omitted] 
  He continued: We want Christianity and Islam to be value 
systems that defend the wronged and oppose the arrogant 
regardless of the consequences. When calculations enter the 
issue, value is lost. If value is lost, what is left of the 
meaning of Islam and Christianity? This is not a position 
against Christianity and Christians. It does not deal with the 
pope's planned visit to Lebanon. We do not oppose the visit. 
We welcome some of its aspects. Undermining causes is a 
different issue. It is not an issue of a papal envoy sent to 
Tunis. A papal envoy should be sent to all those who lost their 
fathers or children in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre, because 
it is these people who can utter the word of truth and ask: 
What is the meaning of the Jews' existence in Palestine? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

