<H3> <TI>   YSP Accuses Northerners of Mobilizing Forces </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    YSP Accuses Northerners of Mobilizing Forces </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0604055894 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 0500 GMT 6 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0604055894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, Yemeni southerners accused northerners of 
mobilizing forces on the former border between the two parts of 
Yemen, considering this a serious military escalation. This 
came in a statement by Ahmad 'Abdallah Salih, deputy secretary 
of the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP]. 
  A responsible source at the General People's Congress [GPC] 
-- a northern official -- responded to these accusations by 
saying that President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih rejected, during the 
Salalah meeting, a southern proposal implying divisionist 
trends, calling for returning all northern and southern military 
units to their pre-unity positions. 
  The same source noted that the Yemeni Presidential Council 
will not be able to hold its scheduled meeting tomorrow because 
the second man in the YSP refuses to come to Sanaa to 
participate in the meeting. 
  It is noteworthy that the Yemeni Presidential Council is a 
collective presidential body including five members -- three 
from the North and two from the South. The two members from the 
South are 'Ali Salim al-Bid and his deputy Salim Salih Muhammad. 

</TEXT>

